üß≠ AI Agent Platform ‚Äì Operational Workflow Guide

Last updated: November 2025

This document explains how to operate your multi-agent system in ChatGPT (GPT-5 Pro Plan).
It covers when to talk to the Project Manager Agent versus the specialist agents, and the correct daily workflow for running and logging work.

‚∏ª

1. Overview of Team Roles

Project Manager Agent (PM Agent)
	‚Ä¢	Central coordinator.
	‚Ä¢	Maintains priorities, tracks health, merges updates, manages TODO, CHANGELOG, and master project file.
	‚Ä¢	Always your starting point for daily planning, progress review, task assignment, and coordination.

Architect Agent
	‚Ä¢	Oversees structure, dependencies, and repo organization.
	‚Ä¢	Handles architecture decisions, folder/file structure, backend ‚Üî frontend consistency.

Frontend Agent
	‚Ä¢	Handles user interface and visual logic (Next.js, Tailwind, components).
	‚Ä¢	Responsible for UI issues, design changes, React/Next component fixes.

Backend Agent
	‚Ä¢	Handles server logic, API routes, Supabase schema, integrations.
	‚Ä¢	Responsible for database logic, API endpoints, Supabase functions.

Workflow Agent
	‚Ä¢	Manages automations and external integrations (Activepieces, Make.com).
	‚Ä¢	Used for automations, event triggers, API bridges.

LLM Trainer Agent
	‚Ä¢	Manages fine-tuning and data prep for OpenAI models.
	‚Ä¢	Handles model training or prompt data updates.

Avatar & Voice Agent
	‚Ä¢	Handles voice/visual assets, TTS/STT, avatars, and media.
	‚Ä¢	Responsible for audio, voice cloning, avatars, animations.

‚∏ª

2. Where to Start Each Day
	1.	Run automation scripts:

./automation/update_memory.sh  
./automation/sync_docs_to_github.sh

This ensures all docs are current and backed up.

	2.	Open the Project Manager Agent chat and send:

/update_master  
Here‚Äôs the current snapshot.  
(Paste or link 00_MASTER_PROJECT.md, TODO.md, CHANGELOG.md)


	3.	Review the Daily Plan that the PM Agent outputs.
Approve or adjust the plan and decide which tasks you‚Äôll handle personally or delegate to the other agents.

‚∏ª

3. How Workflows Are Structured

Communication Hierarchy

You  ‚áÑ  Project Manager Agent  ‚áÑ  Specialist Agents

	‚Ä¢	You tell the PM Agent what needs to happen (feature, bug fix, idea).
	‚Ä¢	The PM Agent decides which specialist agent is responsible.
	‚Ä¢	You then hand off that task to the agent using the PM‚Äôs summary or by directly pasting the relevant request.
	‚Ä¢	This keeps the PM Agent as the single source of truth.

‚∏ª

Typical Task Flow Example

Scenario: You want to fix the onboarding question flow for new AI agent creation.
	1.	You ‚Üí PM Agent:
‚ÄúWe need to refine the question flow during agent creation.‚Äù
	2.	PM Agent ‚Üí You:
It replies:
‚ÄúThis involves Frontend and Backend. Please handoff to Frontend first for UI flow, then Backend for validation logic.‚Äù
	3.	You ‚Üí Frontend Agent:
Paste the PM‚Äôs summary:

/handoff Frontend Agent ‚Äì update the question flow UI as described by PM Agent.  
Here‚Äôs the current issue...


	4.	Frontend Agent:
Writes or revises code.
You test it locally.
When done, ask it:

/summarize_session Summarize what was done today.


	5.	You ‚Üí PM Agent:
‚ÄúFrontend completed the question flow update. Here‚Äôs the summary.‚Äù
The PM Agent logs it, updates TODO and CHANGELOG, and confirms overall status.
	6.	End of Day:
Run update_memory.sh and sync_docs_to_github.sh.

